    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>Best Time to Take Probiotics — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take probiotics in the morning or at night?</summary><p>Both morning and nighttime are effective. The most important factor is consistency — take your probiotic at the same time every day. If choosing, morning (30 minutes before breakfast) has a slight edge because stomach acid is lowest after an overnight fast, providing better survival conditions for acid-sensitive strains like Lactobacillus and Bifidobacterium. Nighttime is also effective if taken 2-3 hours after dinner on a relatively empty stomach.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take probiotics on an empty stomach?</summary><p>Yes — and for most probiotic strains, an empty stomach is actually ideal. Gastric pH is higher (less acidic) when the stomach is empty, which allows more live bacteria to survive transit to the intestines. The optimal protocol is 30 minutes before a meal. Spore-based probiotics (Bacillus strains) are the exception — they can be taken with or without food due to their protective endospore coating.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take probiotics with food?</summary><p>It depends on the strain. Lactobacillus and Bifidobacterium strains survive best when taken before food on an empty stomach. Bacillus (spore-based) probiotics should be taken with food — nutrients may improve spore germination. Saccharomyces boulardii can be taken either way. For multi-strain blends, default to before-food timing to protect the most acid-sensitive strains in the formula.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How long does it take for probiotics to work?</summary><p>Most people notice digestive improvements within 2-4 weeks of consistent daily use. Acute diarrhea may improve within 1-2 days. General digestive comfort typically improves within 1-3 weeks. Immune function benefits appear at 4-8 weeks. Skin conditions may require 8-12 weeks. The timeline depends on the condition, strain, dose, and individual microbiome composition. Consistency is the most critical factor.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take probiotics with other supplements?</summary><p>Yes. Probiotics are safe to combine with most supplements. The best pairing is probiotics with prebiotics (inulin, FOS, GOS) for a synbiotic effect. Probiotics can be taken alongside vitamins, minerals, omega-3s, and most herbal supplements. The only critical timing rule is with antibiotics — maintain a 2-4 hour gap to prevent the antibiotic from killing the probiotic bacteria.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take probiotics every day?</summary><p>Yes. Daily consistency is essential for probiotic effectiveness. Supplemented strains are transient — they pass through the digestive system and need daily replenishment. Clinical trials demonstrating positive outcomes use daily protocols without exception. There is no evidence of tolerance or diminishing returns with long-term daily use. Skipping days allows probiotic populations to decline and delays benefits.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do probiotic gummies work as well as capsules?</summary><p>Probiotic gummies can be effective, but capsules — especially enteric-coated ones — generally deliver more live bacteria to the intestines due to superior acid protection. Gummies expose bacteria to stomach acid immediately upon chewing. To compensate, take gummies on an empty stomach for fastest transit, and look for gummy products with spore-based strains (Bacillus) that are inherently acid-resistant. The CFU count at time of consumption is the key metric to compare.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How long should I take probiotics?</summary><p>Minimum 4-8 weeks to evaluate effectiveness for your specific needs. For ongoing digestive health maintenance, long-term daily use is supported by evidence — studies lasting 6-12 months show sustained benefits without adverse effects. If you stop, supplemented strains decline over 1-3 weeks. For chronic conditions like IBS, ongoing use is typically necessary to maintain benefits. There is no established maximum duration.</p></details>
    </section>

